(This file targets v0.9 provider grammar — it will not compile against
the current v0.8.1 / multi-state-machine grammar. Use as a worked
spec example for the ai-agent compute tool-grant lines.)

(Exercises every source-level grant a Compute can issue:
   - Accesses <list>          read-write (full Content tools)
   - Reads <list>              read-only (query + read only)
   - Sends to "<channel>" channel
   - Emits "<event>"
   - Invokes "<compute>"
 Together these enumerate the full closed tool surface for an agent
 per BRD §6.3.3.)

(Per-app user reputation/profile data is decoupled from the identity
Principal. Identity owns "who authenticated"; the app owns "what we
know about that principal in this app's domain." The two are linked
by Principal.id. Identity-keyed fields use the v0.9 `principal`
business field type per BRD #3 §3.2 — typed at the business layer,
opaque text storage. The compiler enforces that values flowing into
a `principal` field came from a Principal source, not from
arbitrary text input.)

Application: Moderation Agent
  Description: AI moderator that scores incoming messages on a deterministic risk scale, takes action when warranted, alerts human moderators on edge cases, emits events for downstream consumers, and delegates risk scoring to a CEL helper.
Id: 4d1c8e90-5b7a-4e21-a3f8-2c1e5d4b9f01

Identity:
  Scopes are "messages.read", "users.read", "moderation.act", and "moderation.audit"
  Anonymous has "messages.read"
  A "moderator" has "messages.read", "users.read", "moderation.act", and "moderation.audit"
  A "moderation agent" has "messages.read", "users.read", and "moderation.act"

Content called "messages":
  Each message has a body which is text, required
  Each message has an author_principal which is principal, required
  Each message has a posted_at which is automatic
  Anyone with "messages.read" can view messages
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can update or delete messages

(Per-app reputation data, keyed by Principal.id. Not every author has
a row here — a brand-new user posts a message before any reputation
record exists. The agent looks up by author_principal and tolerates a
missing row by treating absence as reputation = 0.)
Content called "user reputation":
  Each user reputation has a principal_id which is principal, unique, required
  Each user reputation has a reputation which is whole number
  Each user reputation has a post_count which is whole number
  Each user reputation has a joined_at which is automatic
  Anyone with "users.read" can view user reputation
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can create or update user reputation

Content called "moderation actions":
  Each moderation action has a target_message which references messages, restrict on delete
  Each moderation action has a verdict which is one of: "ok", "warned", "removed", "user_suspended"
  Each moderation action has a rationale which is text, required
  Each moderation action has a risk_score which is whole number
  Each moderation action has a taken_by_principal which is principal, required
  Each moderation action has a taken_at which is automatic
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can view or create moderation actions
  Anyone with "moderation.audit" can view moderation actions

(Real CEL use: combines four deterministic signals over structured
input to produce a 0-11 risk score. Each signal is independently
auditable and the math is reproducible. Compare to a sentiment
classifier — that would be an llm or ai-agent compute, not CEL,
because it's a learned model rather than expression evaluation.

Signals:
  - Very short messages (< 10 chars): +2  (low-effort spam)
  - Contains a URL: +3                    (link injection risk)
  - All-caps message of meaningful length: +2  (shouting / spam)
  - Author reputation: +4 if negative, +2 if 0..9, 0 otherwise)
Compute called "message risk score":
  Transform: takes message : message and author : user reputation, produces score : whole number
  `score =
     (size(message.body) < 10 ? 2 : 0)
     + (message.body.matches("https?://") ? 3 : 0)
     + (message.body == message.body.upper() && size(message.body) >= 10 ? 2 : 0)
     + (author.reputation < 0 ? 4 : author.reputation < 10 ? 2 : 0)`
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can execute this
  Audit level: none

(Channel the agent uses to ping a human moderator on edge cases.
The Slack / Teams / Discord product binding plus the channel target
live in deploy config, not here.)
Channel called "moderator alerts":
  Provider is "messaging"
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can invoke this channel

  When edge case detected:
    Send a message: `"Edge case on message " + alert.message_id + " — agent confidence " + alert.confidence`

(The agent itself.)
Compute called "review message":
  Provider is "ai-agent"
  Accesses moderation actions               (read-write — agent records its decisions here)
  Reads messages, user reputation           (read-only — agent inspects but never modifies)
  Sends to "moderator alerts" channel       (escalation path for human review)
  Emits "moderation.action_taken"           (downstream consumers subscribe to this)
  Invokes "message risk score"              (delegates deterministic scoring to CEL)
  Trigger on event "message.created"
  Directive is ```
    You are a content moderator. Read the message body and the
    author's per-app reputation row (which may be absent for new
    users). Decide whether the message violates community
    standards. Be cautious with edge cases — if your confidence
    is below 0.8, escalate to a human moderator instead of
    acting unilaterally.
  ```
  Objective is ```
    1. Load the message with content.read("messages", message_id).
    2. Look up the author's reputation with
       content.query("user reputation",
                     {principal_id: message.author_principal}).
       If no row exists, treat reputation as 0.
    3. Call compute.invoke("message risk score",
                           {message: message, author: author_row})
       to get a numeric score.
    4. If score >= 7 OR your own confidence is >= 0.8:
       create a moderation_action with the verdict, rationale,
       risk_score, and your own principal as taken_by_principal.
       Then emit "moderation.action_taken" with the action id.
    5. Else: send to channel "moderator alerts" with the message
       id and your confidence so a human reviews it.
  ```
  Anyone with "moderation.act" can execute this
  Audit level: actions
  Anyone with "moderation.audit" can audit
